From: John Toby Knudsen [mailto:tobyknudsen@gmail.com <mailto:tobyknudsen@gmail.com>] Sent: Wednesday, February 06, 2013 11:01 AM To: Sara Conde Subject: Re: MBO Partners Call Summary Hey Sara,
One thing that is tickling my brain is the prospect of using a domain of mine that is down, www.emacs.org <http://mkto-l0128.com/track?t=c&&&&http://www.emacs.org?mkt_tok=2xUAKZjCb15brEx4%2FviKJ6fNmDjBc5TmuLNwY52MuKVUsyIUGIalUg%3D%3D>, to organize HTML5 and Javascript developers. I've own this domain since 1998 and Emacs is a piece of free software that pre-dates Linux by many years, if this helps to explain anything.
Anyway, 2013 is a transitional year before the W3C gives HTML5 'recommended' status, but all the big players and browsers are behind it. Flash is going away because of it, so people say. Telefonica is embracing Firefox OS which will rely on HTML5, JS, CSS, for example:http://www.openwebdevice.com/ <http://mkto-l0128.com/track?t=c&&&&http://www.openwebdevice.com/?mkt_tok=2xUAKZjCb15brEx4%2FviKJ6fNmDjBc5TmuLNwY52MuKVUsyIUGIalUg%3D%3D>
Let me know if any folks within your organization think this has potential and what form it may take. Besides being a peer developer I could also function in a project management role and all parties could rely on MBO services. This could involve a great number of people as other technologies are dropped in favor of HTML5 and free/open technologies on the back end.
